│ of scalar casts, is being incorrectly called with a vector   │
│ type as its destination (`Dst`) type. This happens when the  │
│ vectorizer is running on the s390x target.\n\n### Analyzing  │
│ `opt`'s Log\n\nThe backtrace clearly shows the call chain    │
│ leading to the crash:\n\n`vectorizeHorReduction` ->          │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` -> `BoUpSLP::getTreeCost` │
│ -> `TTI::getCastInstrCost`\n\nThe crash occurs during the    │
│ cost-modeling phase. The `slp-vectorizer` is attempting to   │
│ vectorize a horizontal reduction. The `tryToReduce` function │
│ builds a temporary SLP tree to model the cost of a potential │
│ transformation. It is during the costing of this temporary   │
│ tree, specifically a `cast` node within it, that the TTI     │
│ function is called with invalid arguments.\n\n### Root Cause │
│ Analysis\n\nThe core of the issue lies in                    │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`. This function attempts   │
│ to vectorize a scalar horizontal reduction (`xor i32, i32`)  │
│ by combining it with an existing vector operation. To model  │
│ this, it creates a temporary `zext` instruction to stand in  │
│ for the scalar value being widened into a vector             │
│ lane.\n\nHowever, the way this is modeled is flawed. The     │
│ `tryToReduce` function creates a `zext` that is already a    │
│ vector instruction (`zext <4 x i1> to <4 x i32>`) and places │
│ it into the `BoUpSLP` tree as if it were a scalar            │
│ instruction to be vectorized. \n\nWhen `getTreeCost`         │
│ processes this node, it treats the vector `zext` as a scalar │
│ and tries to \"vectorize\" it. This leads to incorrect type  │
│ calculations:\n\n1.  `Scalar` instruction in the tree is     │
│ `%zext = zext <4 x i1> %icmp to <4 x i32>`.\n2.              │
│ `getTreeCost` determines the type of the \"vectorized\"      │
│ instruction (`VectorizedInstruction`) by creating a vector   │
│ of the `Scalar`'s type. This results in a type like `<4 x <4 │
│ x i32>>`.\n3.  This vectorized destination type (`<4 x <4 x  │
│ i32>>`) is then passed as the `DstTy` to                     │
│ `TTI.getCastInstrCost`.\n4.  The `SystemZTTIImpl`            │
│ implementation of `getCastInstrCost` asserts                 │
│ `!Dst->isVectorTy()`, as it is only designed to handle       │
│ scalar destination types. The assertion correctly fires      │
│ because it has been passed a vector type.\n\nThe fundamental │
│ problem is that `getTreeCost` is not equipped to handle a    │
│ node that is already a vector instruction, which is what     │
│ `tryToReduce` incorrectly provides it with.\n\n### Proposed  │
│ Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to make `getTreeCost` aware of   │
│ this special case. When it encounters a cast instruction, it │
│ should check if the instruction's destination type is        │
│ already a vector. If it is, we know we are in the special    │
│ scenario created by `tryToReduce`. In this case, we should   │
│ use the instruction's *scalar* operand and result types for  │
│ the cost calculation, rather than trying to create a         │
│ \"vector of vectors\" type.\n\nThis change correctly models  │
│ the cost of a single vector cast instruction, which is what  │
│ `tryToReduce` intended, instead of trying to cost a          │
│ non-existent vector-of-vector-casts                          │
│ operation.\n\n```patch\n---                                  │
│ a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n+++       │
│ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n@@        │
│ -11791,12 +11791,17 @@\n       // We are casting the results │
│ of the vectorized instruction.\n       // The cost is the    │
│ cost of the cast and the cost of the operand.\n       if     │
│ (isa<CastInst>(Scalar)) {\n-        Type *SrcTy =            │
│ VectorizedOperand->getType();\n-        Type *DstTy =        │
│ VectorizedInstruction->getType();\n-        if (SrcTy !=     │
│ DstTy) {\n-          // The cost of the cast is the cost of  │
│ the vector cast.\n-          // TODO: We should be able to   │
│ do this more cleanly.\n+        auto *CI =                   │
│ cast<CastInst>(Scalar);\n+        Type *SrcTy =              │
│ CI->getSrcTy();\n+        Type *DstTy = CI->getDestTy();\n+  │
│ // If the scalar instruction is already a vector cast, we    │
│ are in a\n+        // special case from tryToReduce. We      │
│ should use the scalar types for\n+        // the cost model, │
│ as we are costing a single vector cast, not a\n+        //   │
│ vector of vector casts.\n+        if (DstTy->isVectorTy())   │
│ {\n+          SrcTy = VectorizedOperand->getType();\n+       │
│ DstTy = VectorizedInstruction->getType();\n+        }\n+     │
│ if (VectorizedOperand->getType() !=                          │
│ VectorizedInstruction->getType()) {\n                        │
│ Costs.VectorCost += TTI.getCastInstrCost(\n-                 │
│ cast<CastInst>(Scalar)->getOpcode(), DstTy, SrcTy,\n+        │
│ CI->getOpcode(), DstTy, SrcTy,\n                             │
│ TTI::CastContextHint::Vector, TTI::TCK_RecipThroughput);\n   │
│ }\n       } else {\n```\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe proposed    │
│ patch corrects the logic within `getTreeCost` to handle the  │
│ specific way `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` models       │
│ vectorization costs. By detecting when a cast instruction    │
│ being analyzed is already a vector operation, it avoids      │
│ creating invalid types and passes the correct scalar types   │
│ to the target-specific cost model. This resolves the         │
│ assertion failure in the SystemZ backend and allows the SLP  │
│ vectorizer to correctly assess the cost of the horizontal    │
│ reduction without crashing."})                               │
