│ it into the `BoUpSLP` tree as if it were a scalar            │
│ instruction to be vectorized.\n\nWhen `getTreeCost`          │
│ processes this node, it treats the vector `zext` as a scalar │
│ and tries to \"vectorize\" it. This leads to incorrect type  │
│ calculations:\n\n1.  The `Scalar` instruction in the tree is │
│ `%zext = zext <4 x i1> %icmp to <4 x i32>`.\n2.              │
│ `getTreeCost` determines the type of the \"vectorized\"      │
│ instruction (`VectorizedInstruction`) by creating a vector   │
│ of the `Scalar`'s type. This results in a type like `<4 x <4 │
│ x i32>>`.\n3.  This vectorized destination type (`<4 x <4 x  │
│ i32>>`) is then passed as the `DstTy` to                     │
│ `TTI.getCastInstrCost`.\n4.  The `SystemZTTIImpl`            │
│ implementation of `getCastInstrCost` asserts                 │
│ `!Dst->isVectorTy()`, as it is only designed to handle       │
│ scalar destination types. The assertion correctly fires      │
│ because it has been passed a vector type.\n\nThe fundamental │
│ problem is that `getTreeCost` is not equipped to handle a    │
│ node that is already a vector instruction, which is what     │
│ `tryToReduce` incorrectly provides it with.\n\n### Proposed  │
│ Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to make `getTreeCost` aware of   │
│ this special case. When it encounters a cast instruction, it │
│ should check if the instruction's destination type is        │
│ already a vector. If it is, we know we are in the special    │
│ scenario created by `tryToReduce`. In this case, we should   │
│ use the instruction's *scalar* operand and result types for  │
│ the cost calculation, rather than trying to create a         │
│ \"vector of vectors\" type.\n\nThis change correctly models  │
│ the cost of a single vector cast instruction, which is what  │
│ `tryToReduce` intended, instead of trying to cost a          │
│ non-existent vector-of-vector-casts operation.\n\n###        │
│ Conclusion\n\nThe proposed patch corrects the logic within   │
│ `getTreeCost` to handle the specific way                     │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` models vectorization      │
│ costs. By detecting when a cast instruction being analyzed   │
│ is already a vector operation, it avoids creating invalid    │
│ types and passes the correct scalar types to the             │
│ target-specific cost model. This resolves the assertion      │
│ failure in the SystemZ backend and allows the SLP vectorizer │
│ to correctly assess the cost of the horizontal reduction     │
│ without crashing."                                           │
│ }                                                            │
