  "reason_thou": "### Understanding the Issue\n\nThe
`slp-vectorizer` is crashing with an assertion failure,
`!Dst->isVectorTy()`, inside `SystemZTTIImpl::getCastInstrCost`.
This assertion indicates that the function, which is designed to
calculate the cost of scalar casts, is being incorrectly called
with a vector type as its destination (`Dst`) type. This happens
when the vectorizer is running on the s390x target.\n\n###
Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe backtrace clearly shows the call
chain leading to the crash:\n\n`vectorizeHorReduction` ->
`HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` -> `BoUpSLP::getTreeCost` ->
`TTI::getCastInstrCost`\n\nThe crash occurs during the
cost-modeling phase. The `slp-vectorizer` is attempting to
vectorize a horizontal reduction. The `tryToReduce` function
builds a temporary SLP tree to model the cost of a potential
transformation. It is during the costing of this temporary tree,
specifically a `cast` node within it, that the TTI function is
called with invalid arguments.\n\n### Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe
core of the issue lies in `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`.
This function attempts to vectorize a scalar horizontal
reduction (`xor i32, i32`) by combining it with an existing
vector operation. To model this, it creates a temporary `zext`
instruction to stand in for the scalar value being widened into
a vector lane.\n\nHowever, the way this is modeled is flawed.
The `tryToReduce` function creates a `zext` that is already a
vector instruction (`zext <4 x i1> to <4 x i32>`) and places it
into the `BoUpSLP` tree as if it were a scalar instruction to be
vectorized.\n\nWhen `getTreeCost` processes this node, it treats
the vector `zext` as a scalar and tries to \"vectorize\" it.
This leads to incorrect type calculations:\n\n1.  The `Scalar`
instruction in the tree is `%zext = zext <4 x i1> %icmp to <4 x
i32>`.\n2.  `getTreeCost` determines the type of the
\"vectorized\" instruction (`VectorizedInstruction`) by creating
a vector of the `Scalar`'s type. This results in a type like `<4
x <4 x i32>>`.\n3.  This vectorized destination type (`<4 x <4 x
i32>>`) is then passed as the `DstTy` to
`TTI.getCastInstrCost`.\n4.  The `SystemZTTIImpl` implementation
of `getCastInstrCost` asserts `!Dst->isVectorTy()`, as it is
only designed to handle scalar destination types. The assertion
correctly fires because it has been passed a vector type.\n\nThe
fundamental problem is that `getTreeCost` is not equipped to
handle a node that is already a vector instruction, which is
what `tryToReduce` incorrectly provides it with.\n\n### Proposed
Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to make `getTreeCost` aware of this
special case. When it encounters a cast instruction, it should
check if the instruction's destination type is already a vector.
If it is, we know we are in the special scenario created by
`tryToReduce`. In this case, we should use the instruction's
*scalar* operand and result types for the cost calculation,
rather than trying to create a \"vector of vectors\"
type.\n\nThis change correctly models the cost of a single
vector cast instruction, which is what `tryToReduce` intended,
instead of trying to cost a non-existent vector-of-vector-casts
operation.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe proposed patch corrects the
logic within `getTreeCost` to handle the specific way
`HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` models vectorization costs.
By detecting when a cast instruction being analyzed is already a
vector operation, it avoids creating invalid types and passes
the correct scalar types to the target-specific cost model. This
resolves the assertion failure in the SystemZ backend and allows
the SLP vectorizer to correctly assess the cost of the
horizontal reduction without crashing.",
